00:07:46.570 --> 00:07:50.520
So what is NASA's ambition?

00:07:50.520 --> 00:07:54.650
It's a pretty modest ambition
to try to understand and model

00:07:54.650 --> 00:07:56.000
the whole planet.

00:07:56.000 --> 00:07:58.150
And so this was
actually a diagram.

00:07:58.150 --> 00:07:59.920
It's actually a
famous diagram called

00:07:59.920 --> 00:08:01.720
the Bretherton diagram
that was actually

00:08:01.720 --> 00:08:06.880
created in the late 1980s.

00:08:06.880 --> 00:08:11.560
But it basically
tried to pictorialize

00:08:11.560 --> 00:08:15.680
all of the different
subsystems on the Earth,

00:08:15.680 --> 00:08:18.610
and the interconnected
nature of the subsystems,

00:08:18.610 --> 00:08:22.560
and the challenge of
trying to understand

00:08:22.560 --> 00:08:26.500
the nature of those systems,
but also the interconnections

00:08:26.500 --> 00:08:29.120
of those systems, so
systems of systems.

00:08:29.120 --> 00:08:33.030
And you'll notice there
on the right-hand side

00:08:33.030 --> 00:08:35.370
is the human activities.

00:08:35.370 --> 00:08:37.429
That's not something
that we have focused

00:08:37.429 --> 00:08:40.610
on very much in the history
of the Earth Science program,

00:08:40.610 --> 00:08:42.730
but it's something
that we're beginning

00:08:42.730 --> 00:08:44.350
to really put more focus on.

00:08:44.350 --> 00:08:48.330
And I'll get back
to that in a minute.

00:08:48.330 --> 00:08:50.450
So what do we do to
try to understand

00:08:50.450 --> 00:08:51.890
all of these subsystems?

00:08:51.890 --> 00:08:53.900
This is the current
constellation

00:08:53.900 --> 00:08:55.130
of NASA satellites.

00:08:55.130 --> 00:08:57.380
And so we have
this constellation.

00:08:57.380 --> 00:09:01.060
There are currently
somewhere between 18 and 20

00:09:01.060 --> 00:09:03.800
Earth-observing
satellites from NASA

00:09:03.800 --> 00:09:05.270
that are currently up there.

00:09:05.270 --> 00:09:09.410
And then the color-coding shows
the existing constellation,

00:09:09.410 --> 00:09:11.450
then the missions that
are in development

00:09:11.450 --> 00:09:14.190
and planned for future launch.

00:09:14.190 --> 00:09:17.980
But it's a fairly
complex endeavor.

00:09:17.980 --> 00:09:20.310
People typically
don't think of NASA

00:09:20.310 --> 00:09:22.090
when they think about
doing Earth science,

00:09:22.090 --> 00:09:24.006
but we actually have the
largest Earth science

00:09:24.006 --> 00:09:25.360
program on the planet.

00:09:25.360 --> 00:09:27.670
And it's largely because
it's fairly expensive

00:09:27.670 --> 00:09:30.145
to do these kinds of
space-based missions.

00:09:34.690 --> 00:09:39.470
So this next image
is just an image

00:09:39.470 --> 00:09:42.350
of what these satellites
look like in space.

00:09:42.350 --> 00:09:45.000
And so typically for
Earth observation,

00:09:45.000 --> 00:09:47.730
we have what are called
Sun-synchronous polar orbits,

00:09:47.730 --> 00:09:50.200
which means the
satellites are crossing

00:09:50.200 --> 00:09:52.830
the same place on the
Earth at the same time,

00:09:52.830 --> 00:09:54.390
but they're doing
it in polar orbit

00:09:54.390 --> 00:09:57.240
so that as the Earth
rotates, we eventually

00:09:57.240 --> 00:09:59.410
image the entire planet.

00:09:59.410 --> 00:10:02.130
And so this, again,
is a sequence

00:10:02.130 --> 00:10:03.270
of those constellations.

00:10:03.270 --> 00:10:07.866
One thing you'll notice is
there's a bunch of them.

00:10:07.866 --> 00:10:08.990
I'll show this in a second.

00:10:08.990 --> 00:10:11.930
But there are a bunch of them
that, for the first time,

00:10:11.930 --> 00:10:15.220
we've been attempting
to fly several

00:10:15.220 --> 00:10:19.460
of the satellites
in close formation.

00:10:19.460 --> 00:10:22.000
And basically, that
just leverages the power

00:10:22.000 --> 00:10:28.520
of getting these co-located
in time observations, which

00:10:28.520 --> 00:10:32.460
makes it much easier to
do some of the analysis.

00:10:32.460 --> 00:10:34.480
In the last, oh,
year and a half,

00:10:34.480 --> 00:10:37.080
we've launched a number
of new satellites--

00:10:37.080 --> 00:10:38.950
the Global Precipitation
mission, which

00:10:38.950 --> 00:10:41.180
is-- one of the things
that I didn't say

00:10:41.180 --> 00:10:44.920
is that the work that we do
is very heavily interagency.

00:10:44.920 --> 00:10:47.130
So there are a lot
of agencies in the US

00:10:47.130 --> 00:10:49.110
that have a piece
of Earth science.

00:10:49.110 --> 00:10:51.700
Typically, other
agencies have kind

00:10:51.700 --> 00:10:53.400
of operational responsibility.

00:10:53.400 --> 00:10:55.800
NOAA does weather forecasting.

00:10:55.800 --> 00:11:01.850
USGS does earthquake
observation and response.

00:11:01.850 --> 00:11:06.445
And indeed, a lot of what we do
is we actually build and launch

00:11:06.445 --> 00:11:07.070
the satellites.

00:11:07.070 --> 00:11:08.611
So we build and
launch the satellites

00:11:08.611 --> 00:11:10.180
for NOAA, for the
weather satellites.

00:11:10.180 --> 00:11:12.950
We also-- Landsat
is fundamentally

00:11:12.950 --> 00:11:14.910
a US Geological Survey mission.

00:11:14.910 --> 00:11:17.940
But we build and launch
that satellite as well.

00:11:17.940 --> 00:11:20.660
The Global
Precipitation Mission is

00:11:20.660 --> 00:11:24.280
an example of the international
flavor of what we do.

00:11:24.280 --> 00:11:29.260
And so the Japanese
actually built the radar

00:11:29.260 --> 00:11:32.290
on the GPM mission.

00:11:32.290 --> 00:11:37.880
But if you think about it,
2/3 of the planet is ocean.

00:11:37.880 --> 00:11:41.030
And so other than having these
space-based observations,

00:11:41.030 --> 00:11:43.150
there's no way to get
precipitation measurements

00:11:43.150 --> 00:11:45.590
over the ocean over a
big part of the planet.

00:11:45.590 --> 00:11:48.740
So it's only been since we've
been doing these observations

00:11:48.740 --> 00:11:51.470
from space that we have
a critical component

00:11:51.470 --> 00:11:54.050
of the weather
system on the planet,

00:11:54.050 --> 00:11:57.800
but also how the climate system
is changing, how precipitation

00:11:57.800 --> 00:12:00.260
around the planet is changing.

00:12:00.260 --> 00:12:04.710
SMAP is one of the most recent
missions that we've launched.

00:12:04.710 --> 00:12:08.950
It's the soil
moisture measurement

00:12:08.950 --> 00:12:12.690
using an L-band radar
tuned to humidity

00:12:12.690 --> 00:12:16.440
in the top several
centimeters of soil.

00:12:16.440 --> 00:12:18.010
But again, for
the first time, we

00:12:18.010 --> 00:12:20.990
have a global picture of what
the soil moisture looks like,

00:12:20.990 --> 00:12:25.150
which is hugely important for,
for example, agricultural water

00:12:25.150 --> 00:12:27.250
demand and things like that.

00:12:27.250 --> 00:12:33.060
Unfortunately, SMAP has only
been up for several months.

00:12:33.060 --> 00:12:36.960
And it has two instruments--
a radar and a radiometer.

00:12:36.960 --> 00:12:39.370
They're having problems
with the radar right now.

00:12:39.370 --> 00:12:41.620
We've gotten some
global data sets.

00:12:41.620 --> 00:12:45.290
But right now, the
instrument is being

00:12:45.290 --> 00:12:47.850
debugged to try to figure out
what's going on with the radar.

00:12:47.850 --> 00:12:50.900
We still have the radiometer,
which also provides a soil

00:12:50.900 --> 00:12:55.000
moisture but not with the same
level of spatial resolution

00:12:55.000 --> 00:12:57.240
as the radar instrument.

00:12:57.240 --> 00:12:59.080
I mentioned the
constellation-- we

00:12:59.080 --> 00:13:01.860
refer to it as the A-Train--
which is largely making

00:13:01.860 --> 00:13:03.580
atmospheric measurements.

00:13:03.580 --> 00:13:07.310
And so again, these
satellites are

00:13:07.310 --> 00:13:09.930
flying within a
minute of each other

00:13:09.930 --> 00:13:12.880
in terms of when they actually
cross a particular place

00:13:12.880 --> 00:13:14.310
on the Earth.

00:13:17.290 --> 00:13:19.770
And so I mentioned
one of our challenges

00:13:19.770 --> 00:13:25.270
really is to better understand
the impact of human activity.

00:13:25.270 --> 00:13:28.640
And if you read the little
blurb in the introduction

