00:13:54.780 --> 00:13:58.260
by one of the astronauts--
actually, Don Pettit, who

00:13:58.260 --> 00:14:00.540
actually is from Oregon state.

00:14:00.540 --> 00:14:03.040
But he actually figured out
how to take their cameras-- he

00:14:03.040 --> 00:14:06.920
actually took a Makita drill
and created his own motion

00:14:06.920 --> 00:14:11.260
compensation, because of course,
the space station is traveling

00:14:11.260 --> 00:14:13.990
at thousands of miles an hour.

00:14:13.990 --> 00:14:16.134
And so trying to take
a picture of the Earth

00:14:16.134 --> 00:14:17.300
is a little bit challenging.

00:14:17.300 --> 00:14:18.950
They actually have
much faster cameras.

00:14:18.950 --> 00:14:22.340
This was done probably
close to 10 years ago now.

00:14:22.340 --> 00:14:24.210
But the really
neat thing that you

00:14:24.210 --> 00:14:27.370
can see from night lights
images, particularly these ones

00:14:27.370 --> 00:14:29.940
from the space station which
are much higher resolution

00:14:29.940 --> 00:14:34.220
than the other satellites where
you've seen night light images,

00:14:34.220 --> 00:14:40.080
you can really start to see not
just the presence of humans,

00:14:40.080 --> 00:14:43.180
but you can see different
aspects of human activity.

00:14:43.180 --> 00:14:47.090
For example, you can easily pick
out transportation corridors.

00:14:47.090 --> 00:14:49.480
You can pick out
industrial sections.

00:14:49.480 --> 00:14:51.470
Cities-- you can see
San Francisco there

00:14:51.470 --> 00:14:54.990
at the top end of the Bay
is very brightly colored.

00:14:54.990 --> 00:14:57.190
And so one of the
things that you can do

00:14:57.190 --> 00:15:01.090
is begin to use this as a
surrogate for where the carbon

00:15:01.090 --> 00:15:02.390
emissions are.

00:15:02.390 --> 00:15:04.900
That's not so much of a
problem in the United States

00:15:04.900 --> 00:15:08.440
because we have a lot of other
information that tells us that.

00:15:08.440 --> 00:15:10.804
But around the rest of
the world and particularly

00:15:10.804 --> 00:15:12.220
the developed
countries that don't

00:15:12.220 --> 00:15:15.610
have that kind of
data-taking capability,

00:15:15.610 --> 00:15:18.670
it's a really nice way to
pinpoint where the carbon

00:15:18.670 --> 00:15:22.380
emissions are coming from
in terms of writing carbon

00:15:22.380 --> 00:15:24.090
treaties and things like that.

00:15:24.090 --> 00:15:26.510
The other fantastic
thing about night lights

00:15:26.510 --> 00:15:30.400
which I find really
intriguing is the extent

00:15:30.400 --> 00:15:34.330
to which you can see the impacts
of human decision-making.

00:15:34.330 --> 00:15:37.920
And so we all very much
benefit in the Bay Area

00:15:37.920 --> 00:15:41.020
from decisions that were
made in the '50s and '60s

00:15:41.020 --> 00:15:44.030
where people set aside
open space in the Bay Area.

00:15:44.030 --> 00:15:45.420
So what you see
there, of course,

00:15:45.420 --> 00:15:48.990
is Silicon Valley, San Francisco
at the top end of the Bay,

00:15:48.990 --> 00:15:50.780
San Jose at the bottom end.

00:15:50.780 --> 00:15:53.780
But what you don't see
is where the mountains

00:15:53.780 --> 00:15:57.490
are, because we've
kept development out

00:15:57.490 --> 00:16:00.430
of the hills for the most part.

00:16:00.430 --> 00:16:03.580
And so you can see that very
clearly in an image like this.

00:16:03.580 --> 00:16:08.060
It's even actually more
striking in this image,

00:16:08.060 --> 00:16:10.760
which is of Washington DC.

00:16:10.760 --> 00:16:13.220
And for those of you know
that know Washington DC,

00:16:13.220 --> 00:16:16.400
you know that it was
developed as a 10 mile

00:16:16.400 --> 00:16:20.780
on a side square turned on
its side so it's a diamond.

00:16:20.780 --> 00:16:23.700
But the remarkable thing to
me, the very bright lights

00:16:23.700 --> 00:16:27.200
are kind of the central
DC, the mall area.

00:16:27.200 --> 00:16:30.920
But you can see the outline
of that 10 mile square

00:16:30.920 --> 00:16:33.950
in this image with
nothing other than lights.

00:16:33.950 --> 00:16:37.070
And so basically
what that says is

00:16:37.070 --> 00:16:40.580
that people are making
decisions in one neighborhood

00:16:40.580 --> 00:16:42.950
about nighttime
lighting that are

00:16:42.950 --> 00:16:45.210
very different from the
community next door.

00:16:45.210 --> 00:16:51.310
So it's a very powerful tool
for looking at human presence,

00:16:51.310 --> 00:16:55.370
changing human
presence, and impacts

00:16:55.370 --> 00:17:00.270
of human policy management
decisions on the Earth--

00:17:00.270 --> 00:17:03.640
pretty exciting stuff.

00:17:03.640 --> 00:17:07.440
Right now, the regular
satellite images

00:17:07.440 --> 00:17:09.869
are much lower resolution
than these images.

00:17:09.869 --> 00:17:11.990
We at NASA Ames have
really pushed hard

00:17:11.990 --> 00:17:16.980
to get NASA to think about
putting up a night light

00:17:16.980 --> 00:17:19.390
imager that would give you
this kind of resolution,

00:17:19.390 --> 00:17:21.802
and you could really do
some interesting things.

00:17:21.802 --> 00:17:23.260
I'm going to talk
a little bit more

00:17:23.260 --> 00:17:25.343
about public/private
partnerships in a little bit.

00:17:25.343 --> 00:17:30.760
But I think this is one
where if we don't do it

00:17:30.760 --> 00:17:34.020
in the government, I'm
hopeful that others will find

00:17:34.020 --> 00:17:37.640
this interesting and valuable
enough to actually look

00:17:37.640 --> 00:17:40.610
at doing.

00:17:40.610 --> 00:17:43.790
So one of the other things
that we do at NASA--

00:17:43.790 --> 00:17:47.460
and because we can't see all
of the detailed geophysical

00:17:47.460 --> 00:17:52.450
phenomenon from space just
because we're so far away--

00:17:52.450 --> 00:17:56.760
and it is interesting how
it's changing all the time

00:17:56.760 --> 00:17:58.610
in terms of our capabilities.

00:17:58.610 --> 00:18:01.670
But one of the other tools
that we have in the tool set

00:18:01.670 --> 00:18:03.290
is aircraft.

00:18:03.290 --> 00:18:06.230
And so NASA has
historically had aircraft

00:18:06.230 --> 00:18:09.300
that focus on high
altitude measurements.

00:18:09.300 --> 00:18:12.690
So that aircraft in the
upper left, for example,

00:18:12.690 --> 00:18:16.820
is really a converted
U-2 spy plane

00:18:16.820 --> 00:18:20.580
that we've converted to do
geophysical measurements.

00:18:20.580 --> 00:18:22.820
We've had that since
the early '70s.

00:18:22.820 --> 00:18:26.660
We actually started the NASA
Airborne Program at NASA Ames

00:18:26.660 --> 00:18:28.440
back in the '70s.

00:18:28.440 --> 00:18:29.975
You notice that we
paint ours white

00:18:29.975 --> 00:18:33.480
because we're the good guys.

00:18:33.480 --> 00:18:36.460
But more recently,
we've been starting

00:18:36.460 --> 00:18:38.480
to use the NASA
Global Hawk, which

00:18:38.480 --> 00:18:40.890
is the aircraft on the
upper right, which is kind

00:18:40.890 --> 00:18:43.075
of a replacement for the U-2.

00:18:43.075 --> 00:18:45.740
It flies roughly the
same altitude, roughly

00:18:45.740 --> 00:18:47.620
the same payload capability.

00:18:47.620 --> 00:18:50.730
But it really allows us to
get to places on the planet,

00:18:50.730 --> 00:18:52.670
particularly in the
upper atmosphere, that we

00:18:52.670 --> 00:18:55.190
just-- there's no
other way to get

00:18:55.190 --> 00:18:57.090
to those kinds of measurements.

00:18:57.090 --> 00:19:00.920
And so again, even though
people don't really

00:19:00.920 --> 00:19:02.920
think of Earth science
when they think of NASA,

00:19:02.920 --> 00:19:06.990
we actually have the
largest airborne program

00:19:06.990 --> 00:19:09.660
of any agency on
the planet as well.

00:19:09.660 --> 00:19:12.180
The DC-8 in the
lower left is just

00:19:12.180 --> 00:19:15.110
an old commercial airliner,
but we've pretty much

00:19:15.110 --> 00:19:17.490
stripped it completely bare
so that we can actually

00:19:17.490 --> 00:19:22.270
put laboratory-size
instruments in that aircraft.

00:19:22.270 --> 00:19:24.830
And we have a really nice
program every summer.

00:19:24.830 --> 00:19:27.330
It's actually called the Student
Airborne Research Program.

00:19:27.330 --> 00:19:29.740
So if any students out
there in the audience

00:19:29.740 --> 00:19:31.590
are interested in
doing this, we actually

00:19:31.590 --> 00:19:35.370
bring in about 30 students
from around the country.

00:19:35.370 --> 00:19:37.580
We actually put instruments
on the aircraft.

00:19:37.580 --> 00:19:40.870
That's a picture of some of
the students on the aircraft.

00:19:40.870 --> 00:19:42.230
They take the data.

00:19:42.230 --> 00:19:44.619
They develop their
own research project.

00:19:44.619 --> 00:19:46.160
And then they actually
take the data,

00:19:46.160 --> 00:19:48.530
do their research and
analysis, and then

00:19:48.530 --> 00:19:50.550
present it at the
end of the summer.

00:19:50.550 --> 00:19:54.290
It's a really exciting program,
really hands-on opportunity

00:19:54.290 --> 00:19:55.965
to do Earth science.

00:19:58.890 --> 00:20:03.540
And so one of the prime examples
of how the airborne program

00:20:03.540 --> 00:20:07.010
really plays is
that in the 1980s,

00:20:07.010 --> 00:20:09.170
there was the ozone hole,
and nobody really knew

00:20:09.170 --> 00:20:11.100
what was going on with that.

00:20:11.100 --> 00:20:14.390
NASA actually had just launched
the Total Ozone Mapping

00:20:14.390 --> 00:20:16.440
Spectrometer, or TOMS.

00:20:16.440 --> 00:20:23.490
And so we could see those
images of the globe looking down

00:20:23.490 --> 00:20:25.090
on the South Pole.

00:20:25.090 --> 00:20:27.910
We could see the ozone
hole, but we couldn't

00:20:27.910 --> 00:20:29.510
determine what was causing it.

00:20:29.510 --> 00:20:34.190
So there were several
theories at the time.

00:20:34.190 --> 00:20:36.249
Nitric oxide is
released by aircraft.

00:20:36.249 --> 00:20:38.040
And there was a concern
that there was just

00:20:38.040 --> 00:20:41.310
a climatological shift in
the circulation patterns.

00:20:41.310 --> 00:20:43.720
But one of the top
contenders was CFC,

00:20:43.720 --> 00:20:46.930
is the chlorofluorocarbons
and whether those were really

00:20:46.930 --> 00:20:48.020
causing the ozone hole.

00:20:48.020 --> 00:20:51.610
It wasn't until we were able
to take our high altitude

00:20:51.610 --> 00:20:54.950
aircraft, which was really
the only way in the world

00:20:54.950 --> 00:20:57.670
to get these measurements,
and we actually went down

00:20:57.670 --> 00:21:00.970
based out of Punta Arenas, which
is on the Strait of Magellan

00:21:00.970 --> 00:21:03.820
at the southern tip
of South America.

00:21:03.820 --> 00:21:05.910
And we are able to make
measurements directly

00:21:05.910 --> 00:21:09.550
into the ozone hole which was in
the stratosphere over the South

00:21:09.550 --> 00:21:10.570
Pole.

00:21:10.570 --> 00:21:13.240
And we were able to bring
back what we've always

00:21:13.240 --> 00:21:14.680
referred to as the smoking gun.

00:21:14.680 --> 00:21:18.020
It showed that there was
this tremendous correlation

00:21:18.020 --> 00:21:20.005
with the chlorine
molecules that we

00:21:20.005 --> 00:21:22.620
were seeing, which ended up
being the source of the ozone

00:21:22.620 --> 00:21:23.580
hole.

00:21:23.580 --> 00:21:27.980
And the exciting thing
about that for us

00:21:27.980 --> 00:21:31.420
is that that data that
we took fed directly

00:21:31.420 --> 00:21:34.030
into international policy,
which became the Montreal

00:21:34.030 --> 00:21:37.850
Protocol which basically
calls all the developed

00:21:37.850 --> 00:21:42.050
countries to phase out
the development of CFCs.

00:21:42.050 --> 00:21:46.780
And we averted losing
our stratospheric ozone

00:21:46.780 --> 00:21:50.064
layer, which protects us.

00:21:50.064 --> 00:21:50.730
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:21:50.730 --> 00:21:51.370
-NASA scientists
are joining with--

00:21:51.370 --> 00:21:53.610
STEVE HIPSKIND: This is
just a quick video clip

00:21:53.610 --> 00:21:55.420
of some of the other
more recent work

00:21:55.420 --> 00:21:58.020
that we've done with the
Global Hawk aircraft.

00:21:58.020 --> 00:22:01.800
But essentially, we put
instruments on that aircraft.

00:22:01.800 --> 00:22:04.400
And in this case, we were
very interested in what's

00:22:04.400 --> 00:22:07.050
the impact of climate
change on the water

00:22:07.050 --> 00:22:09.680
cycle, and particularly,
how does water vapor

00:22:09.680 --> 00:22:11.520
go from the lowest
part of the atmosphere

00:22:11.520 --> 00:22:13.110
into the stratosphere?

00:22:13.110 --> 00:22:15.470
Because if you get more
water in the stratosphere,

00:22:15.470 --> 00:22:19.210
it actually has a huge
impact on the ozone cycle

00:22:19.210 --> 00:22:23.630
and potentially leads to
more ozone production.

00:22:23.630 --> 00:22:27.310
And so we actually-- again,
this was really the only way

00:22:27.310 --> 00:22:30.270
to get that data in
the upper atmosphere

00:22:30.270 --> 00:22:33.220
over the middle of the Pacific.

00:22:33.220 --> 00:22:35.990
The Global Hawk gives us
a new measurement domain

00:22:35.990 --> 00:22:38.840
because it can stay up in
the air for 31 hours compared

00:22:38.840 --> 00:22:41.757
to the U-2, which can stay up
for only about eight hours.

00:22:41.757 --> 00:22:42.340
[END PLAYBACK]

00:22:42.340 --> 00:22:42.980
STEVE HIPSKIND: And
so we're actually

00:22:42.980 --> 00:22:44.660
able to go get
those measurements.

00:22:44.660 --> 00:22:47.470
And indeed in this project
that we got funded here

00:22:47.470 --> 00:22:50.690
at NASA Ames, we actually
showed that there's much more

00:22:50.690 --> 00:22:52.600
water vapor getting
into the stratosphere

00:22:52.600 --> 00:22:54.120
than people had anticipated.

00:22:54.120 --> 00:22:58.320
So again, our stuff
is not quite as sexy

00:22:58.320 --> 00:23:02.100
as doing a flyby of the planets,
but it's really the stuff

00:23:02.100 --> 00:23:05.940
that NASA does that's most
directly impactful to life

00:23:05.940 --> 00:23:07.600
here on Earth.

00:23:07.600 --> 00:23:10.380
Another thing that we've
done with aircraft,

00:23:10.380 --> 00:23:13.280
this is actually a satellite
image of the big wildfires

00:23:13.280 --> 00:23:14.310
in Southern California.

00:23:14.310 --> 00:23:17.340
This was actually in 2007.

00:23:17.340 --> 00:23:19.700
But again, the
satellite gives you

00:23:19.700 --> 00:23:21.570
kind of the overall picture.

00:23:21.570 --> 00:23:24.810
But in terms of decision
making for the firefighters,

00:23:24.810 --> 00:23:28.470
it's not nearly enough detail.

00:23:28.470 --> 00:23:32.020
And so we embarked
on this program

00:23:32.020 --> 00:23:36.320
where we put a very high
dynamic-range infrared

00:23:36.320 --> 00:23:42.220
sensor on the Ikhana UAV
and really changed the way

00:23:42.220 --> 00:23:43.950
that the US fights fires.

00:23:43.950 --> 00:23:47.320
We actually worked with
folks in Terry's organization

00:23:47.320 --> 00:23:49.780
and intelligent
systems and took some

00:23:49.780 --> 00:23:53.860
of the autonomy and intelligent
planning and scheduling,

00:23:53.860 --> 00:23:57.980
and repurposed actually software
that was developed for the Mars

00:23:57.980 --> 00:24:03.490
rovers, and repurposed that for
managing the data coming down

00:24:03.490 --> 00:24:05.380
from the UAV.

00:24:05.380 --> 00:24:09.480
Put together a satellite
link, on-board processing

00:24:09.480 --> 00:24:12.500
on the aircraft so that
we were able to generate--

00:24:12.500 --> 00:24:16.920
So the image on the left
there is what the firefighter

00:24:16.920 --> 00:24:17.750
sees on the ground.

00:24:17.750 --> 00:24:20.730
It's very hard to see kind
of where the fire fronts are,

00:24:20.730 --> 00:24:23.310
where it is relative
to the terrain.

00:24:23.310 --> 00:24:25.210
And so with the
infrared sensor, we're

00:24:25.210 --> 00:24:27.790
able look through
the smoke, determine

00:24:27.790 --> 00:24:30.330
where the hot spots are or
where the fire fronts are.

00:24:30.330 --> 00:24:32.490
And then we actually
use Google Earth

00:24:32.490 --> 00:24:34.670
because that was
very standardized

00:24:34.670 --> 00:24:37.200
in the firefighting
community, and we're

00:24:37.200 --> 00:24:38.700
able to show them
where these fire

00:24:38.700 --> 00:24:41.130
fronts were and were moving.

00:24:41.130 --> 00:24:43.190
And so they, for
the first time ever,

00:24:43.190 --> 00:24:46.460
used real-time data that we
were giving them from NASA.

00:24:46.460 --> 00:24:49.190
And they were using that to make
decisions about putting boots

00:24:49.190 --> 00:24:50.560
on the ground.

00:24:50.560 --> 00:24:53.850
Typically, they had done
infrared imagery before,

00:24:53.850 --> 00:24:57.170
but they would go up in an
aircraft, take the data.

00:24:57.170 --> 00:24:58.470
Aircraft would land.

00:24:58.470 --> 00:25:00.630
There would be a group that
would process the data.

00:25:00.630 --> 00:25:04.220
And maybe six hours later, the
firefighters got those images.

00:25:04.220 --> 00:25:06.690
Well, a lot happens in
six hours in a big fire.

00:25:06.690 --> 00:25:09.030
So we were giving
them real-time images.

00:25:09.030 --> 00:25:12.210
And indeed, we were
doing basically

00:25:12.210 --> 00:25:15.500
a web-based distribution so
our data was going directly

00:25:15.500 --> 00:25:19.600
onto the incident command center
set up for the big wildfires.

00:25:19.600 --> 00:25:21.190
And that was going
up on their boards

00:25:21.190 --> 00:25:23.670
within five minutes
of taking the data.

00:25:23.670 --> 00:25:26.370
And so NASA doesn't fight fires.

00:25:26.370 --> 00:25:28.240
And so one of our
challenges is kind

00:25:28.240 --> 00:25:29.910
of the research operations.

00:25:29.910 --> 00:25:32.710
How do we transfer
this technology

00:25:32.710 --> 00:25:34.630
into the hands of
the agency who has

00:25:34.630 --> 00:25:36.750
the responsibility-- in
this case, the US Forest

00:25:36.750 --> 00:25:38.690
Service-- for fighting fires?

00:25:38.690 --> 00:25:41.390
And so they've
actually adopted what

00:25:41.390 --> 00:25:43.360
we referred to as a
Collaborative Decision

00:25:43.360 --> 00:25:44.670
Environment, the software.

00:25:44.670 --> 00:25:47.790
And that now they use that at
NIFC, the National Interagency

00:25:47.790 --> 00:25:49.780
Fire Center, in Boise.

00:25:49.780 --> 00:25:52.220
And they actually use that
software to manage wildfires

00:25:52.220 --> 00:25:54.340
across the United States.

00:25:54.340 --> 00:25:56.220
We also gave them,
on permanent loan,

00:25:56.220 --> 00:25:57.960
the infrared sensor
so they actually

00:25:57.960 --> 00:26:00.560
can duplicate the capabilities
that we demonstrated.

00:26:05.030 --> 00:26:11.605
We're more recently looking at
using smaller robotic aircraft.

00:26:11.605 --> 00:26:15.730
The images in the left there
are of our Sierra aircraft,

00:26:15.730 --> 00:26:19.590
which we went from not
ever using this for science

00:26:19.590 --> 00:26:23.380
to going to Svalbard, which
is the island owned by

00:26:23.380 --> 00:26:26.010
and north of Norway, so
above the Arctic Circle.

00:26:26.010 --> 00:26:29.680
So we kind of went from testing
this thing out here at Ames

00:26:29.680 --> 00:26:32.420
to going to one of the
most extreme environments

00:26:32.420 --> 00:26:33.350
on the planet.

00:26:33.350 --> 00:26:34.980
But we demonstrated
that you can fly

00:26:34.980 --> 00:26:38.590
these aircraft for about 10
hours and return useful data.

00:26:38.590 --> 00:26:41.140
In this case, we were looking
at the surface roughness

00:26:41.140 --> 00:26:45.180
of the Arctic ice sheets
to look at can you

00:26:45.180 --> 00:26:48.850
determine the age of the
ice from remote sensing

00:26:48.850 --> 00:26:53.830
and improve your remote
sensing algorithms from space.

00:26:53.830 --> 00:26:55.910
The image in the
lower right there

00:26:55.910 --> 00:26:58.190
is actually some much
smaller aircraft-- actually,

00:26:58.190 --> 00:26:59.780
Dragon Eyes.

00:26:59.780 --> 00:27:01.980
And we were able to
work with, actually

00:27:01.980 --> 00:27:06.710
in this case, NASA JPL that
had a very small SO2 sensor.

00:27:06.710 --> 00:27:10.680
And we were able to fly
these-- this is actually

00:27:10.680 --> 00:27:13.409
Mount Turrialba in Costa Rica.

00:27:13.409 --> 00:27:15.200
And so we were actually
able to demonstrate

00:27:15.200 --> 00:27:17.320
that we could fly
these aircraft actually

00:27:17.320 --> 00:27:20.900
at much higher than they had
originally been intended to fly

00:27:20.900 --> 00:27:25.100
and we could look at sulfur
dioxide emissions coming out

00:27:25.100 --> 00:27:26.600
of the volcanoes.

00:27:26.600 --> 00:27:28.760
And so our next step
actually this summer

00:27:28.760 --> 00:27:32.490
is to fly these
aircraft in formation,

00:27:32.490 --> 00:27:34.800
and so rather than having
to talk individually

00:27:34.800 --> 00:27:36.990
to the aircraft, talk
to them as a group,

00:27:36.990 --> 00:27:41.600
and be able to do broader
spatial measurements

00:27:41.600 --> 00:27:45.490
with these small platforms.

00:27:45.490 --> 00:27:48.420
And then another-- so
this is a little bit

00:27:48.420 --> 00:27:49.845
of the public/private
partnership.

00:27:49.845 --> 00:27:51.220
I don't know how
many of you know

00:27:51.220 --> 00:27:53.900
that your principals
actually have

00:27:53.900 --> 00:27:56.160
a bunch of private aircraft
that they keep over

00:27:56.160 --> 00:27:58.140
at Moffett Field.

00:27:58.140 --> 00:28:01.510
And one of the quid pro quos of
this public/private partnership

00:28:01.510 --> 00:28:04.830
is they've allowed us to put
our scientific instruments

00:28:04.830 --> 00:28:07.510
on this aircraft that they own.

00:28:07.510 --> 00:28:08.960
It's called an Alpha Jet.

00:28:08.960 --> 00:28:11.840
And so we've developed
a greenhouse gas

00:28:11.840 --> 00:28:18.220
payload that we put on there
to measure CO2, methane, ozone,

00:28:18.220 --> 00:28:20.430
water vapor, et cetera.

00:28:20.430 --> 00:28:22.810
And the image in
the middle there,

00:28:22.810 --> 00:28:25.550
one of the things that we do
with satellite observations

00:28:25.550 --> 00:28:28.370
that the aircraft program
is very helpful for

00:28:28.370 --> 00:28:31.790
is doing validation of
the satellite images.

00:28:31.790 --> 00:28:34.270
So we look at places
on the planet.

00:28:34.270 --> 00:28:35.960
This is Railroad
Valley, which is

00:28:35.960 --> 00:28:41.560
a very high, very uniform playa
in the high desert in Nevada.

00:28:41.560 --> 00:28:43.680
But with this partnership,
we can actually

00:28:43.680 --> 00:28:46.630
make very routine measurements
that we wouldn't otherwise

00:28:46.630 --> 00:28:49.550
be able to make if
we had to propose

00:28:49.550 --> 00:28:52.520
to use the NASA aircraft,
which are in very high demand.

00:28:52.520 --> 00:28:54.320
So we've been making
these measurements

00:28:54.320 --> 00:28:58.170
over Railroad Valley every
month for the last five years.

00:28:58.170 --> 00:29:01.260
So it's a very powerful tool.

00:29:01.260 --> 00:29:03.224
And this is just a little image.

00:29:03.224 --> 00:29:03.890
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:29:03.890 --> 00:29:06.306
STEVE HIPSKIND: We were working
with the Japanese who also

00:29:06.306 --> 00:29:08.320
are measuring CO2 from space.

00:29:08.320 --> 00:29:10.940
So this is a Japanese
team that were actually

00:29:10.940 --> 00:29:15.576
in Railroad Valley
making measurements

00:29:15.576 --> 00:29:18.020
of CO2 and methane.

00:29:18.020 --> 00:29:21.640
So we're able to fly the Alpha
Jet from here at Moffett Field

00:29:21.640 --> 00:29:23.600
and fly right over that playa.

00:29:23.600 --> 00:29:26.245
And then we have them circle
up and do a vertical profile

00:29:26.245 --> 00:29:28.770
to compare to the
satellite measurements.

00:29:28.770 --> 00:29:33.020
So it's a really
exciting capability.

00:29:33.020 --> 00:29:34.890
It's actually kind
of fun because we

00:29:34.890 --> 00:29:37.450
try to get the profiles as
close to the surface as we can.

00:29:37.450 --> 00:29:38.024
-[INAUDIBLE].

00:29:38.024 --> 00:29:40.190
STEVE HIPSKIND: This is
probably a little bit closer

00:29:40.190 --> 00:29:41.890
than we expected them to do.

00:29:41.890 --> 00:29:45.154
But you can't say we're
not close to the surface

00:29:45.154 --> 00:29:46.906
with those measurements.

00:29:46.906 --> 00:29:47.489
[END PLAYBACK]

00:29:47.489 --> 00:29:51.210
And so what do we do with
all of this information?

00:29:51.210 --> 00:29:55.380
The whole idea is to try to
not only understand, but to be

00:29:55.380 --> 00:29:58.060
able to predict what's going
to happen in the future.

00:29:58.060 --> 00:30:00.220
This is a really
nice, colorful image

00:30:00.220 --> 00:30:02.000
of some modeling work
that's actually done

00:30:02.000 --> 00:30:04.430
at NASA Goddard in Maryland.

00:30:04.430 --> 00:30:07.570
But it's looking at
the atmospheric aerosol

00:30:07.570 --> 00:30:11.280
and it's color coded
by aerosol source,

00:30:11.280 --> 00:30:15.200
but very high resolution
meteorological analyses

00:30:15.200 --> 00:30:19.490
showing how aerosols, for
example, from Saharan Africa

00:30:19.490 --> 00:30:22.840
get transported
across the Atlantic.

00:30:22.840 --> 00:30:26.850
So again, this is the ultimate
goal of that Bretherton

00:30:26.850 --> 00:30:29.570
diagram, is to put all
of this information

00:30:29.570 --> 00:30:32.860
together and be able to
predict into the future.

00:30:32.860 --> 00:30:36.550
One of the things that
we're doing at NASA Ames

00:30:36.550 --> 00:30:39.620
is what we call the
NASA Earth Exchange.

00:30:39.620 --> 00:30:41.660
It's actually very
similar to-- and we've

00:30:41.660 --> 00:30:43.440
had some collaborative
relationships

00:30:43.440 --> 00:30:48.510
with the Google Earth
Engine folks here at Google.

00:30:48.510 --> 00:30:52.360
But we can use that
to really assimilate

00:30:52.360 --> 00:30:55.800
all of these very
large satellite data

00:30:55.800 --> 00:30:58.930
sets into a single
place and then have

00:30:58.930 --> 00:31:02.180
the data co-located with
the various analytics

00:31:02.180 --> 00:31:04.600
and large models.

00:31:04.600 --> 00:31:06.620
In this particular
case, we're using

00:31:06.620 --> 00:31:10.290
it to look at irrigation
demand in the Central

00:31:10.290 --> 00:31:11.560
Valley of the US.

00:31:11.560 --> 00:31:13.730
We had done a lot of
work up at Napa Valley,

00:31:13.730 --> 00:31:15.860
doing that for grapes.

00:31:15.860 --> 00:31:20.005
So we had the opportunity a
few years ago to scale this up.

00:31:20.005 --> 00:31:22.130
And now, we're looking at
the whole Central Valley.

00:31:22.130 --> 00:31:24.670
But we're showing
that you can actually

00:31:24.670 --> 00:31:29.060
reduce the amount
of irrigated water

00:31:29.060 --> 00:31:31.840
to kind of an optimum
level, still maintain

00:31:31.840 --> 00:31:35.100
the same level of
agricultural productivity,

00:31:35.100 --> 00:31:38.232
but fairly significantly
reduce the water.

00:31:38.232 --> 00:31:41.234
In some side-by-side tests
in the Salinas Valley,

00:31:41.234 --> 00:31:43.900
we were able to demonstrate that
you could maintain productivity

00:31:43.900 --> 00:31:46.382
with up to 35%
reduction in water.

00:31:46.382 --> 00:31:48.590
You're not going to get that
across the whole Central

00:31:48.590 --> 00:31:52.350
Valley, but even if
you could save 5% to 7%

00:31:52.350 --> 00:31:57.240
of the water usage in
California, that would be huge.

00:31:57.240 --> 00:32:00.340
Another thing that we've been
able to do with the NASA Earth

00:32:00.340 --> 00:32:03.200
Exchange is climate downscaling.

00:32:03.200 --> 00:32:06.460
We've actually recently scaled
this up to the whole planet.

00:32:06.460 --> 00:32:10.100
But this is taking the IPCC,
the Intergovernmental Panel

00:32:10.100 --> 00:32:13.590
on Climate Change, and kind
of the best models that

00:32:13.590 --> 00:32:16.640
come out of that group.

00:32:16.640 --> 00:32:18.410
I thought that was
set up to repeat,

00:32:18.410 --> 00:32:22.860
but let me see if I
can show that again.

00:32:22.860 --> 00:32:27.860
This is basically just showing
from current to 2100 what

00:32:27.860 --> 00:32:31.530
the state of the art model show
for temperature in the United

00:32:31.530 --> 00:32:34.140
States, which actually,
if you look at this,

00:32:34.140 --> 00:32:34.920
it's pretty scary.

00:32:34.920 --> 00:32:37.340
Because you can see that
the whole central part

00:32:37.340 --> 00:32:39.670
of the United States
actually looks

00:32:39.670 --> 00:32:43.290
a lot like the southwestern
United States by 2100.

00:32:43.290 --> 00:32:48.480
That's using the scenario of
not a lot of carbon reduction.

00:32:48.480 --> 00:32:50.370
But it's really
kind of the scenario

00:32:50.370 --> 00:32:51.590
that we're currently on.

00:32:51.590 --> 00:32:55.620
So it's actually a pretty
accurate portrayal.

00:32:55.620 --> 00:32:58.280
One other example I'll
show really quickly-- this

00:32:58.280 --> 00:33:02.160
is some recent work mapping
fallowed fields in California,

00:33:02.160 --> 00:33:06.380
again, just using remote sensing
but using fairly sophisticated

00:33:06.380 --> 00:33:11.730
analysis tools to get to what's
a fallow field versus just

00:33:11.730 --> 00:33:13.530
roadway or whatever.

00:33:13.530 --> 00:33:17.200
And so we're
producing these maps.

00:33:17.200 --> 00:33:20.180
This is from 2011 to 2015.

00:33:20.180 --> 00:33:24.340
But you can track the increasing
amount of fallowed fields

00:33:24.340 --> 00:33:26.440
in the Central Valley,
which is basically

00:33:26.440 --> 00:33:30.780
a direct impact of the drought
on California agriculture.

00:33:30.780 --> 00:33:34.410
And so this work has been used
by the California Department

00:33:34.410 --> 00:33:41.810
of Water Resources to brief the
governor's drought task force.

00:33:41.810 --> 00:33:44.360
It actually just
came out last week

00:33:44.360 --> 00:33:49.740
in a White House missive on
what is the US government doing

00:33:49.740 --> 00:33:51.270
to address climate change.

00:33:51.270 --> 00:33:55.540
So this data was
featured in that as well.

00:33:55.540 --> 00:33:58.200
So I'm going to quickly shift
gears and talk about some

00:33:58.200 --> 00:34:01.840
of the interesting stuff that
we're doing at Ames in looking

00:34:01.840 --> 00:34:05.360
at, again, remote sensing.

00:34:05.360 --> 00:34:09.960
This is what we end up
calling fluid lensing.

00:34:09.960 --> 00:34:12.510
But in my humble
opinion, I actually

00:34:12.510 --> 00:34:15.800
think this has the possibility
of completely revolutionizing

00:34:15.800 --> 00:34:19.380
the way we do remote sensing.

00:34:19.380 --> 00:34:22.750
And so what you're
seeing here is an image

00:34:22.750 --> 00:34:24.500
of the Venus transit
of the Sun that

00:34:24.500 --> 00:34:26.440
happened several years ago.

00:34:26.440 --> 00:34:28.489
And so this is an
image of the Sun.

00:34:28.489 --> 00:34:33.159
Of course, the black spot is
the Venus transit of the Sun.

00:34:33.159 --> 00:34:36.449
But the remarkable
thing is we were

00:34:36.449 --> 00:34:40.721
able to get this kind of detail
on the surface of the Sun.

00:34:40.721 --> 00:34:42.179
And you would think
that that might

00:34:42.179 --> 00:34:46.850
be a satellite circulating
around the sun,

00:34:46.850 --> 00:34:49.139
but this is actually
the telescope

00:34:49.139 --> 00:34:51.360
that those images
were taken from.

00:34:51.360 --> 00:34:54.789
And so normally when you
have a piece of glass,

00:34:54.789 --> 00:34:56.330
that gives you the
diffraction limit.

00:34:56.330 --> 00:34:59.700
It limits your spatial
resolution that you can see.

00:34:59.700 --> 00:35:05.240
But what this young researcher
Ved Chirayath is doing

00:35:05.240 --> 00:35:08.210
is actually using atmospheric
turbulence as a lens.

00:35:08.210 --> 00:35:11.660
And so it basically gets
around the limitation

00:35:11.660 --> 00:35:15.170
of having to put big giant
pieces of glass in space

00:35:15.170 --> 00:35:17.240
and allows you to
use the atmosphere

00:35:17.240 --> 00:35:19.610
to lens those images.

00:35:19.610 --> 00:35:22.760
And so I actually got him to
do some work in Earth science.

00:35:22.760 --> 00:35:25.810
And so I asked him if he
could take that same technique

00:35:25.810 --> 00:35:29.260
and look downward,
and what could you do.

00:35:29.260 --> 00:35:32.830
And so he actually recognized
that one really interesting

00:35:32.830 --> 00:35:37.530
thing that you could do
is imaging shallow water

00:35:37.530 --> 00:35:39.010
ecosystems.

00:35:39.010 --> 00:35:42.880
And so this is actually an
image at the Stanford pool.

00:35:42.880 --> 00:35:45.920
That's Ved on the
right looking up.

00:35:45.920 --> 00:35:51.220
And so he's got a little logo
that's hung above the pool.

00:35:51.220 --> 00:35:52.740
And you can see
that's what it would

00:35:52.740 --> 00:35:55.770
look like if you're sitting
on the bottom of the pool.

00:35:55.770 --> 00:35:59.870
But if you apply the fluid
lensing-- so basically

00:35:59.870 --> 00:36:02.400
in this case, you're using
that air/water interface

00:36:02.400 --> 00:36:03.680
in the waves.

00:36:03.680 --> 00:36:06.050
And you can imagine that
when the wave goes by,

00:36:06.050 --> 00:36:10.840
it actually acts as a lens and
it both magnifies and sharpens

00:36:10.840 --> 00:36:11.510
the image.

00:36:11.510 --> 00:36:14.720
And so you can go from that
image in the upper left

00:36:14.720 --> 00:36:18.540
to that image in the lower left.

00:36:18.540 --> 00:36:20.460
So you can see that it
actually is slightly

00:36:20.460 --> 00:36:24.810
magnified from the real image,
but it also basically gives you

00:36:24.810 --> 00:36:27.500
an accurate portrayal
of what's really there.

00:36:27.500 --> 00:36:29.100
And so he's taken this.

00:36:29.100 --> 00:36:34.180
He's actually put it on
a small quadcopter UAV.

00:36:34.180 --> 00:36:35.900
And he's imaged two places now.

00:36:35.900 --> 00:36:39.280
One was the coral reefs
in American Samoa.

00:36:39.280 --> 00:36:42.010
And this is actually in
Shark Bay in Australia

00:36:42.010 --> 00:36:45.210
where there are these
stromatolite pools.

00:36:45.210 --> 00:36:48.730
Stromatolites are the oldest
living organisms on the planet.

00:36:48.730 --> 00:36:52.440
They're responsible for creating
the oxygen in the atmosphere.

00:36:52.440 --> 00:36:54.030
And this is the
first time anyone's

00:36:54.030 --> 00:36:56.360
ever gotten permission
to actually do

00:36:56.360 --> 00:36:59.890
flying over a remote
sensing of Hamelin Pool.

00:36:59.890 --> 00:37:02.870
But this is what you would
see from that imagery

00:37:02.870 --> 00:37:04.710
if you're just flying along.

00:37:04.710 --> 00:37:07.390
And this is applying the
fluid lensing technique.

00:37:07.390 --> 00:37:10.020
So he's actually
generated literally

00:37:10.020 --> 00:37:12.650
centimeter scale,
three-dimensional images

00:37:12.650 --> 00:37:16.780
of both these stromatolites
as well as the coral reefs.

00:37:16.780 --> 00:37:19.930
And it gives you this
incredibly powerful capability,

00:37:19.930 --> 00:37:22.670
for the first time, to
use a remote sensing

00:37:22.670 --> 00:37:25.690
to do things like
identify species

00:37:25.690 --> 00:37:27.400
differentiation in coral reefs.

00:37:27.400 --> 00:37:30.990
And so you can look at
impacts of changing climate

00:37:30.990 --> 00:37:35.970
on specific species
in the coral reefs.

00:37:35.970 --> 00:37:41.780
So I'll finish by
just saying that we

00:37:41.780 --> 00:37:45.530
as humans on this planet
face tremendous issues

00:37:45.530 --> 00:37:47.110
environmentally.

00:37:47.110 --> 00:37:51.210
And it really takes much
more than the US government

00:37:51.210 --> 00:37:52.350
or all the governments.

00:37:52.350 --> 00:37:55.080
It takes all of us
working on these problems.

00:37:55.080 --> 00:37:57.600
And so I really
personally feel that

00:37:57.600 --> 00:38:01.750
public/private partnerships are
an important way going forward

00:38:01.750 --> 00:38:06.240
in that it's really
a way to leverage

00:38:06.240 --> 00:38:10.370
the financial resources
that companies like Google

00:38:10.370 --> 00:38:12.550
and others can
bring to the table

00:38:12.550 --> 00:38:15.960
and looking at
different ways to get

00:38:15.960 --> 00:38:20.320
these measurements or different
ways to analyze that data.

00:38:20.320 --> 00:38:23.240
This actually looks
like a cartoon picture.

00:38:23.240 --> 00:38:26.170
This is actually the
launch of some CubeSats

00:38:26.170 --> 00:38:28.330
from the International
Space Station.

00:38:28.330 --> 00:38:30.390
That one in the
center is actually

00:38:30.390 --> 00:38:32.910
what was referred to as
PhoneSat at the time.

00:38:32.910 --> 00:38:35.100
But it's the same
guys that were working

00:38:35.100 --> 00:38:37.770
at Ames that went off and
created Planet Labs up

00:38:37.770 --> 00:38:40.380
in San Francisco.

00:38:40.380 --> 00:38:45.530
But I think it's really
important for private sector

00:38:45.530 --> 00:38:48.580
companies, like Skybox,
like Planet Labs,

00:38:48.580 --> 00:38:50.980
to really push the
federal government.

00:38:50.980 --> 00:38:56.510
Because we're not the most
fast-paced nimble organization

00:38:56.510 --> 00:39:01.130
on the planet, but there's
sort of this balance.

00:39:01.130 --> 00:39:06.990
Because it's important to have
the sort of the long-term view,

00:39:06.990 --> 00:39:11.670
which the US government
has, combined with sort

00:39:11.670 --> 00:39:14.050
of new capabilities, new ideas.

00:39:14.050 --> 00:39:16.300
And I think that's
the way that we're

00:39:16.300 --> 00:39:19.260
going to move forward and
solve some of these problems

00:39:19.260 --> 00:39:20.130
that we face.

00:39:20.130 --> 00:39:21.460
So thank you very much.

00:39:21.460 --> 00:39:22.392
Appreciate being here.

00:39:22.392 --> 00:39:24.256
