00:39:35.140 --> 00:39:36.431
STEVE HIPSKIND: Oh, absolutely.

00:39:36.431 --> 00:39:39.090
So I mean, there's a tremendous
amount of compute power

00:39:39.090 --> 00:39:43.370
that-- I mean, so
those original images

00:39:43.370 --> 00:39:47.140
were created with a GoPro,
which is pretty remarkable when

00:39:47.140 --> 00:39:49.960
you see what he was
able to retrieve.

00:39:49.960 --> 00:39:52.050
But he's actually
gotten some funding

00:39:52.050 --> 00:39:54.060
from the Earth Science
Technology office, which

00:39:54.060 --> 00:39:56.600
is our technology
development at NASA,

00:39:56.600 --> 00:40:00.370
to build much more
sophisticated cameras which also

00:40:00.370 --> 00:40:04.230
have incredibly
powerful CPUs on them

00:40:04.230 --> 00:40:06.280
to do the image processing.

00:40:06.280 --> 00:40:09.640
It's essentially machine
vision because you

00:40:09.640 --> 00:40:12.900
have to look at the
scale of the turbulence,

00:40:12.900 --> 00:40:14.560
and then you have
to figure that out.

00:40:14.560 --> 00:40:17.010
And then you have to be able
to stitch all that together.

00:40:17.010 --> 00:40:20.600
So it's a pretty
challenging problem.

00:40:20.600 --> 00:40:25.120
But we've actually just put in
a proposal to put those cameras,

00:40:25.120 --> 00:40:27.710
which are kind of
state-of-the-art video cameras.

00:40:27.710 --> 00:40:31.550
I think they are 4K
by 4K imagers that are

00:40:31.550 --> 00:40:33.720
doing like 90 images a second.

00:40:33.720 --> 00:40:35.390
So it's a tremendous
amount of data

00:40:35.390 --> 00:40:38.360
that's being generated,
a tremendous problem

00:40:38.360 --> 00:40:41.380
to solve in terms of
just processing the data.

00:40:41.380 --> 00:40:43.955
But we're hoping that that
proposal will be successful

00:40:43.955 --> 00:40:45.780
and we'll launch these
things into space

00:40:45.780 --> 00:40:48.800
and test what he's
done on a quadcopter

00:40:48.800 --> 00:40:50.290
from space, see what we can get.

00:40:50.290 --> 00:40:51.480
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:40:51.480 --> 00:40:53.350
STEVE HIPSKIND: So
the dome actually

00:40:53.350 --> 00:40:56.710
covers a large
steerable antenna.

00:40:56.710 --> 00:40:59.520
And so of course, we're
dependent on satellite

00:40:59.520 --> 00:41:01.380
communication to
use that aircraft

00:41:01.380 --> 00:41:04.750
because we're typically sending
it from Southern California.

00:41:04.750 --> 00:41:07.500
We can send it all the way
to Australian and back.

00:41:07.500 --> 00:41:12.460
So we need a way to communicate
with the aircraft in flight.

00:41:12.460 --> 00:41:15.960
So yeah, so there's a
big rotating dish that

00:41:15.960 --> 00:41:18.310
sits under that big dome.

00:41:18.310 --> 00:41:20.620
Unfortunately for us, it
takes a lot of payload space,

00:41:20.620 --> 00:41:22.620
so we complain about that.

00:41:22.620 --> 00:41:24.190
We'd like them to
shrink the dish.

00:41:24.190 --> 00:41:27.230
But if any of you
guys have any ideas--

00:41:27.230 --> 00:41:29.900
And one of the challenges
that we face in Earth science

00:41:29.900 --> 00:41:31.650
is there's so many
things that we

00:41:31.650 --> 00:41:34.720
need to understand that
it's hard to sort of pick--

00:41:34.720 --> 00:41:38.780
in fact, we as a community
have a hard time prioritizing

00:41:38.780 --> 00:41:42.460
where we should put
our resources because

00:41:42.460 --> 00:41:44.080
of that reason.

00:41:44.080 --> 00:41:46.520
In fact, one of the
things that NASA does

00:41:46.520 --> 00:41:49.460
is it seeks input
from the community

00:41:49.460 --> 00:41:51.780
through the National
Research Council.

00:41:51.780 --> 00:41:53.850
And we actually--
every 10 years, we

00:41:53.850 --> 00:41:56.490
generate what's called
a Decadal Survey.

00:41:56.490 --> 00:42:00.500
And so we actually ask know the
smartest people in the country

00:42:00.500 --> 00:42:03.500
to give us those priorities.

00:42:03.500 --> 00:42:07.582
I think more and
more, one thing that's

00:42:07.582 --> 00:42:09.040
becoming more and
more important is

00:42:09.040 --> 00:42:12.530
spatial resolution and
the ability to see things

00:42:12.530 --> 00:42:13.664
at much finer detail.

00:42:13.664 --> 00:42:15.080
Because we're
getting to the point

00:42:15.080 --> 00:42:18.250
where our models can
actually give us--

00:42:18.250 --> 00:42:23.280
we're getting projections down
to regional and local scales,

00:42:23.280 --> 00:42:29.290
but we need the data sets to
corroborate the model results.

00:42:29.290 --> 00:42:33.830
And so clearly, spatial
resolution is a big one.

00:42:33.830 --> 00:42:36.570
Just coming up with new
kinds of measurements.

00:42:36.570 --> 00:42:41.250
I didn't show it, but the
results from the soil moisture

00:42:41.250 --> 00:42:44.820
measurement-- we showed
the global picture of soil

00:42:44.820 --> 00:42:46.980
moisture, and it's
hugely impactful.

00:42:46.980 --> 00:42:48.840
Because again, for
the first time,

00:42:48.840 --> 00:42:51.690
you have this global picture
of what things look like.

00:42:51.690 --> 00:42:54.810
Unfortunately, one of the
things that was most striking

00:42:54.810 --> 00:42:58.610
is how similar Saharan Africa
was to the Western United

00:42:58.610 --> 00:43:02.150
States now in terms
of soil moisture.

00:43:02.150 --> 00:43:05.990
But yeah, so it's is very
hard to pick top priorities.

00:43:05.990 --> 00:43:09.390
I mean, I think we're sort
of moving down that road.

00:43:09.390 --> 00:43:11.220
The global precipitation
measurement

00:43:11.220 --> 00:43:14.136
has been huge in terms
of understanding.

00:43:14.136 --> 00:43:15.760
That's one of the
biggest uncertainties

00:43:15.760 --> 00:43:18.405
that we have now in climate
models is understanding

00:43:18.405 --> 00:43:20.280
what climate change will
do to precipitation.

00:43:23.080 --> 00:43:26.560
One of our big
focuses at NASA Ames

00:43:26.560 --> 00:43:30.300
is better trying to understand
clouds and aerosols,

00:43:30.300 --> 00:43:35.170
because they're, again,
one of the largest

00:43:35.170 --> 00:43:39.120
uncertainties in our ability
to the forecast climate.

00:43:39.120 --> 00:43:41.470
Because depending
on the type of cloud

00:43:41.470 --> 00:43:44.880
and the location of the
cloud in the atmosphere,

00:43:44.880 --> 00:43:47.700
it can either have a heating
effect or a cooling effect,

00:43:47.700 --> 00:43:53.030
and so better understanding
that phenomenon.

00:43:53.030 --> 00:43:57.700
In fact, we just got funded--
a little plug for us.

00:43:57.700 --> 00:44:00.030
We just got funded for
a five year project

00:44:00.030 --> 00:44:04.240
where we're going to base
actually the ER-2 aircraft out

00:44:04.240 --> 00:44:08.280
of Western Africa.

00:44:08.280 --> 00:44:11.530
And there's a phenomenon
there similar to the West

00:44:11.530 --> 00:44:14.180
Coast of the United States where
you get a low strata stack,

00:44:14.180 --> 00:44:16.840
but they have an awful
lot of biomass burning.

00:44:16.840 --> 00:44:19.885
And so you get the smoke that
comes off of the continent.

00:44:19.885 --> 00:44:22.910
It creates a bunch of the
aerosol that generates

00:44:22.910 --> 00:44:25.510
cloud condensation nuclei.

00:44:25.510 --> 00:44:28.780
And so it's a perfect
place on the planet for us

00:44:28.780 --> 00:44:31.390
to try to better understand
how you distinguish

00:44:31.390 --> 00:44:35.740
between these aerosol particles
and the clouds underneath them.

00:44:35.740 --> 00:44:39.010
And so in that one,
you really need

00:44:39.010 --> 00:44:41.360
those very detailed
measurements that you can only

00:44:41.360 --> 00:44:43.110
get from an aircraft.

00:44:43.110 --> 00:44:51.300
So I guess my wish list is
to change the NASA budget

00:44:51.300 --> 00:44:52.430
by an order of magnitude.

00:44:52.430 --> 00:44:54.760
How about that?

00:44:54.760 --> 00:44:58.510
How do you get the data back to
farmers in an actionable way?

00:44:58.510 --> 00:45:02.620
Well, so that's again
an excellent question.

00:45:02.620 --> 00:45:06.280
And indeed, one of
really the strengths

00:45:06.280 --> 00:45:09.470
of that project that we're
doing in the Central Valley

00:45:09.470 --> 00:45:12.890
is that we're working with the
California Department of Water

00:45:12.890 --> 00:45:16.660
Resources who has an
irrigation forecast system.

00:45:16.660 --> 00:45:18.840
We're working with the
Western Growers Association.

00:45:18.840 --> 00:45:22.340
We're working with a number of
growers, both large and small.

00:45:22.340 --> 00:45:25.409
So some of the growers
have approached us

00:45:25.409 --> 00:45:26.950
because they've
heard about the work.

00:45:26.950 --> 00:45:30.770
So we just, about a
year ago, had Gallo come

00:45:30.770 --> 00:45:33.090
and ask to be part
of this program.

00:45:33.090 --> 00:45:35.760
And so we work very
much hand and glove

00:45:35.760 --> 00:45:38.550
with the growers to see
what their needs are.

00:45:38.550 --> 00:45:41.300
If you notice that one
little image I showed,

00:45:41.300 --> 00:45:47.220
the ultimate is to have it on
a smartphone or a mobile device

00:45:47.220 --> 00:45:48.720
because the farmers
typically aren't

00:45:48.720 --> 00:45:51.472
sitting at their computers
back in their homes.

00:45:51.472 --> 00:45:52.930
They're typically
out in the field,

00:45:52.930 --> 00:45:54.860
trying to figure
out what's going on.

00:45:54.860 --> 00:45:57.890
So we are definitely
working with them

00:45:57.890 --> 00:46:00.820
to figure out what
best meets their needs.

00:46:00.820 --> 00:46:05.660
Again, classic case,
though, of sort of NASA--

00:46:05.660 --> 00:46:08.050
we're a research and
development agency.

00:46:08.050 --> 00:46:09.720
We're not an operational agency.

00:46:09.720 --> 00:46:13.410
So for us, when we demonstrate
these things, part of it

00:46:13.410 --> 00:46:16.660
is just kind of figuring out
how to hand that technology off,

00:46:16.660 --> 00:46:21.570
either to private companies
that will sell those services,

00:46:21.570 --> 00:46:25.640
or other agencies like the
US Department of Agriculture

00:46:25.640 --> 00:46:28.220
that can adopt some
of these capabilities.

00:46:28.220 --> 00:46:31.404
And they have a whole
agricultural research service

00:46:31.404 --> 00:46:33.570
where they could actually
adopt some of these things

00:46:33.570 --> 00:46:36.010
and have it as one
of their capabilities

00:46:36.010 --> 00:46:38.590
that they can share
with the farmers.

00:46:38.590 --> 00:46:41.950
AUDIENCE: Do you release
your own measurements data

00:46:41.950 --> 00:46:42.760
to the public?

00:46:42.760 --> 00:46:44.700
Or do you think it
would make sense or not?

00:46:44.700 --> 00:46:46.556
STEVE HIPSKIND: Aw,
a great question.

00:46:46.556 --> 00:46:48.180
I'm glad you asked
because that was one

00:46:48.180 --> 00:46:50.470
of the points I meant to make.

00:46:50.470 --> 00:46:53.720
NASA and the United
States absolutely

00:46:53.720 --> 00:46:58.680
sort of lead the world in the
fact that any data that we take

00:46:58.680 --> 00:47:02.570
becomes publicly available
to everybody on the planet

00:47:02.570 --> 00:47:04.360
when we take it.

00:47:04.360 --> 00:47:06.510
And that's actually
pushing a number

00:47:06.510 --> 00:47:13.970
of other space-faring countries
to change their data policies.

00:47:13.970 --> 00:47:17.800
But yeah, that's one of
the beauties of what we do

00:47:17.800 --> 00:47:20.410
is we make that data
publicly available.

00:47:20.410 --> 00:47:24.550
And so we actually have a
data system that was set up

00:47:24.550 --> 00:47:28.320
when we started on this program
of Earth Observation System,

00:47:28.320 --> 00:47:30.090
EOS.

00:47:30.090 --> 00:47:33.950
And indeed, we actually set up
a data distribution system back

00:47:33.950 --> 00:47:36.120
before there was
a World Wide Web.

00:47:36.120 --> 00:47:40.030
And so there's some
challenging-- I mean,

00:47:40.030 --> 00:47:41.930
NASA has tried to keep up.

00:47:41.930 --> 00:47:46.390
But I think what we're doing at
NASA Ames with the NASA Earth

00:47:46.390 --> 00:47:49.570
Exchange and what you guys
are doing with Google Earth

00:47:49.570 --> 00:47:51.860
Engine are exactly
the kind of things

00:47:51.860 --> 00:47:57.360
that we need to be pushing
forward in that right now,

00:47:57.360 --> 00:48:01.430
these data sets are in different
archives around the country.

00:48:01.430 --> 00:48:04.300
And so the typical
thing is for scientists

00:48:04.300 --> 00:48:08.820
to go download that data and
run it on their home computer.

00:48:08.820 --> 00:48:14.110
And it was interesting in
that NEX and Google Earth

00:48:14.110 --> 00:48:17.510
Engine had a very similar
heritage in that they

00:48:17.510 --> 00:48:22.180
both recognize that compute
power has vastly improved.

00:48:22.180 --> 00:48:25.160
Storage has become
easier and cheaper,

00:48:25.160 --> 00:48:27.860
but bandwidth hasn't
really kept up.

00:48:27.860 --> 00:48:30.420
So really, the idea is
bringing all that data

00:48:30.420 --> 00:48:33.070
next to the analytics
and the models

00:48:33.070 --> 00:48:35.820
so that people have
much more direct access

00:48:35.820 --> 00:48:38.890
and so everybody's not trying
to move big, giant quantities

00:48:38.890 --> 00:48:41.640
of data across the network.

00:48:41.640 --> 00:48:44.180
But that's facilitated
by the fact

00:48:44.180 --> 00:48:49.490
that all of this data that we
create is publicly available.

00:48:49.490 --> 00:48:51.910
AUDIENCE: You showed the
pictures of the ozone hole

00:48:51.910 --> 00:48:55.140
over Antarctica and
it didn't look--

00:48:55.140 --> 00:48:58.360
even though the accord was made
a reasonably long time ago,

00:48:58.360 --> 00:49:03.430
it didn't look like it was
closing significantly by 2000.

00:49:03.430 --> 00:49:04.930
It wasn't growing,
I agree with you.

00:49:04.930 --> 00:49:06.971
STEVE HIPSKIND: Well, I
don't remember, actually,

00:49:06.971 --> 00:49:07.930
which years I showed.

00:49:07.930 --> 00:49:08.721
That was probably--

00:49:08.721 --> 00:49:10.240
AUDIENCE: 2011 was
the latest one.

00:49:10.240 --> 00:49:10.750
STEVE HIPSKIND: Pardon?

00:49:10.750 --> 00:49:11.380
AUDIENCE: 2011 was the latest.

00:49:11.380 --> 00:49:12.255
STEVE HIPSKIND: Yeah.

00:49:12.255 --> 00:49:14.240
Well, and so the
interesting thing about that

00:49:14.240 --> 00:49:19.110
is one of the challenges with
that is that the CFCs-- I mean,

00:49:19.110 --> 00:49:21.930
they were developed
in the 1930s to be

00:49:21.930 --> 00:49:23.940
extremely stable molecules.

00:49:23.940 --> 00:49:27.990
And so they have a very long
lifetime in the atmosphere.

00:49:27.990 --> 00:49:31.380
And so we expected in
the late '80s, early '90s

00:49:31.380 --> 00:49:33.860
when they were looking
at Montreal Protocol

00:49:33.860 --> 00:49:36.570
that it would probably
be about mid-century

00:49:36.570 --> 00:49:39.570
because these molecules
have about a 50 to 60

00:49:39.570 --> 00:49:41.385
year lifetime in the atmosphere.

00:49:41.385 --> 00:49:43.010
So it would probably
about mid-century.

00:49:43.010 --> 00:49:45.680
So what we do see-- I mean,
we monitor this stuff.

00:49:45.680 --> 00:49:47.800
And so what we do
see is that there's

00:49:47.800 --> 00:49:51.930
been a tremendous reduction--
well, a reduction in the growth

00:49:51.930 --> 00:49:54.840
rate, and actually, a reduction
in the total amount of chlorine

00:49:54.840 --> 00:49:56.950
getting into the stratosphere.

00:49:56.950 --> 00:50:00.050
But you know, it's got such
a long lag in the system

00:50:00.050 --> 00:50:03.030
that we don't expect
the ozone hole

00:50:03.030 --> 00:50:06.860
to completely come
back to pre-1980s

00:50:06.860 --> 00:50:08.635
until some time around 2050.

00:50:08.635 --> 00:50:11.760
So come back and talk
to me then and we'll

00:50:11.760 --> 00:50:14.380
let you know if our
theories are right.

00:50:14.380 --> 00:50:17.320
AUDIENCE: So I know you
said that you guys have

00:50:17.320 --> 00:50:20.430
the largest Earth science
group doing research.

00:50:20.430 --> 00:50:22.450
Is budget always a concern?

00:50:22.450 --> 00:50:25.930
How do you guys lobby to get
more money or spread education

00:50:25.930 --> 00:50:27.180
about earth science and stuff?

00:50:27.180 --> 00:50:28.679
STEVE HIPSKIND: So
that's the beauty

00:50:28.679 --> 00:50:31.590
of being a civil servant.

00:50:31.590 --> 00:50:34.260
As NASA, we're an
executive agency.

00:50:34.260 --> 00:50:36.550
So we actually work
for the president.

00:50:36.550 --> 00:50:41.510
And so if we lobby,
we go to jail.

00:50:41.510 --> 00:50:46.010
So we can only do outreach
and talk about the great work

00:50:46.010 --> 00:50:52.950
we do, but we are explicitly
prohibited from lobbying.

00:50:52.950 --> 00:50:56.490
But as you can imagine, it
is a very political thing.

00:50:56.490 --> 00:51:00.410
And for those of us that are
very critically dependent--

00:51:00.410 --> 00:51:03.570
so we work for the
president, but the Congress

00:51:03.570 --> 00:51:05.090
sets our budget.

00:51:05.090 --> 00:51:08.680
And if you follow
the Congress, you

00:51:08.680 --> 00:51:10.090
know that there's
a certain party

00:51:10.090 --> 00:51:14.880
in the country that's not that
interested in climate change.

00:51:14.880 --> 00:51:20.300
And so they actually tried to
cut our budget by about $600

00:51:20.300 --> 00:51:22.880
million this year.

00:51:22.880 --> 00:51:31.320
Luckily, there's a lot of
political theater that goes on.

00:51:31.320 --> 00:51:34.860
But when it comes down to
actually generating the budget,

00:51:34.860 --> 00:51:37.300
I think saner heads prevail.

00:51:37.300 --> 00:51:41.490
And so our budget looks like
it's going to be fairly stable.

00:51:41.490 --> 00:51:43.380
So that's one of our
challenges, is just

00:51:43.380 --> 00:51:46.340
trying to make sure that we have
some stability in the budget

00:51:46.340 --> 00:51:50.510
because these missions
are fairly expensive.

00:51:50.510 --> 00:51:53.530
And so when we get these
big radical shifts from year

00:51:53.530 --> 00:51:56.592
to year, we have
quite a few people

00:51:56.592 --> 00:51:58.050
that are working
on these missions,

00:51:58.050 --> 00:52:00.410
and it's hard to start and stop.

00:52:00.410 --> 00:52:07.560
And so for us, it's really
just a matter of recognizing--

00:52:07.560 --> 00:52:10.450
I mean, you can only really
take the pulse of the planet

00:52:10.450 --> 00:52:11.990
if you're making
the measurements.

00:52:11.990 --> 00:52:17.700
And so the more that
we can get people

00:52:17.700 --> 00:52:22.360
to appreciate the importance of
those continuous measurements,

00:52:22.360 --> 00:52:23.360
the better.

00:52:23.360 --> 00:52:29.160
But I mean, our opportunity
is to try to educate people

00:52:29.160 --> 00:52:31.680
as much as possible.

00:52:31.680 --> 00:52:36.760
And it's interesting
in that I think-- well,

00:52:36.760 --> 00:52:40.180
and so our budget, so in
the last Decadal Survey

00:52:40.180 --> 00:52:43.880
that the National Research
Council did, for example,

00:52:43.880 --> 00:52:47.090
they gave us a wish
list of a program that

00:52:47.090 --> 00:52:49.280
probably would have taken
at least twice the budget

00:52:49.280 --> 00:52:50.820
that we have now.

00:52:50.820 --> 00:52:56.590
And so we try to maintain
a stable executable program

00:52:56.590 --> 00:52:59.860
but knowing that we can't
do everything that people

00:52:59.860 --> 00:53:00.890
would like us to do.

00:53:00.890 --> 00:53:03.050
And then you get
into conversations

00:53:03.050 --> 00:53:06.550
about national priorities
and what's more important.

00:53:06.550 --> 00:53:12.010
But I personally feel
that if we're really

00:53:12.010 --> 00:53:15.890
going to try to make progress
in addressing climate change,

00:53:15.890 --> 00:53:17.720
it can't be just the
federal government.

00:53:17.720 --> 00:53:21.610
It's got to be all of us--
from individual actions,

00:53:21.610 --> 00:53:24.030
but also corporate
actions, which

00:53:24.030 --> 00:53:27.300
can be challenging because
of course, corporations

00:53:27.300 --> 00:53:32.220
have different responsibilities
to, say, shareholders.

00:53:32.220 --> 00:53:35.760
And so I mean, we've
entered into a number

00:53:35.760 --> 00:53:38.490
of public/private partnerships.

00:53:38.490 --> 00:53:41.010
But just getting
the conversation

00:53:41.010 --> 00:53:44.260
going and speaking the same
language can be a challenge.

00:53:44.260 --> 00:53:49.860
And so I think working toward
those goals is, in my view,

00:53:49.860 --> 00:53:52.390
very important.

00:53:52.390 --> 00:53:54.760
But I think part of it
is just getting people

00:53:54.760 --> 00:53:57.320
to understand the
challenges that we face

00:53:57.320 --> 00:54:00.530
and what it takes to
understand and address them.

00:54:00.530 --> 00:54:01.780
FEMALE SPEAKER: OK, thank you.

00:54:01.780 --> 00:54:03.030
STEVE HIPSKIND: OK, thank you.

